📝 Problem Statement:
In an infinite table tennis game, three players (Sosai, Fofo, and Hohai) play matches under the following rules:
1️⃣ Two players play while the third spectates.
2️⃣ A player who plays twice in a row must sit out the next match.
3️⃣ Otherwise, the winner and the spectator of the previous match will play the next one.
Given an integer k, determine if the first spectator will still be spectating in the k-th match.
🔹 Input:
t (1 ≤ t ≤ 1000) — number of test cases.
For each test case: k (1 ≤ k ≤ 10⁹) — match number.
🔹 Output:
For each test case, print "YES" if the first spectator remains a spectator in the k-th match, otherwise print "NO".
🔍 Observations & Approach:
If we track the spectator positions, we find a pattern:
The first spectator remains a spectator in rounds where k % 3 == 1.
Otherwise, they will have played by that round.
Thus, the problem simplifies to checking whether k % 3 == 1.
💡 C++ Solution:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

void solve() {
    int k;
    cin >> k;
    cout << (k % 3 == 1 ? "YES" : "NO") << "\n";
}

int main() {
    int t;
    cin >> t;
    while (t--) solve();
    return 0;
}
🔹 Time Complexity: O(1) per test case, O(t) overall.
