When implementing Binary Search, we need to calculate the middle index (mid) to determine which half of the array to search next. There are two commonly used ways to compute mid:
✅ Using (left + right) / 2
int mid = (left + right) / 2;
This is the straightforward and intuitive way to calculate the middle index. However, in some programming languages where integers have a limited range (like C++ and Java), adding left and right directly might cause integer overflow if they are large values.
✅ Using left + (right - left) / 2
int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
This avoids the potential overflow issue because we first subtract left from right, ensuring that we work with a smaller number before adding it back to left.
🔹 Example in Binary Search
Here’s an example of a correct binary search implementation using the safe mid calculation:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int binarySearch(int arr[], int n, int target) {
    int left = 0, right = n - 1;

    while (left <= right) {
        int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
        if (arr[mid] == target)
            return mid;
        else if (arr[mid] < target)
            left = mid + 1;
        else
            right = mid - 1;
    }

    return -1; 
}

int main() {
    int arr[] = {1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11};
    int n = sizeof(arr) / sizeof(arr[0]);
    int target = 7;

    int index = binarySearch(arr, n, target);
    if (index != -1)
        cout << "Element found at index: " << index << endl;
    else
        cout << "Element not found" << endl;

    return 0;
}
🔥 Conclusion
mid = (left + right) / 2; is simple but might cause overflow.
mid = left + (right - left) / 2; is the recommended approach to prevent overflow issues.
Always prefer the safe version when working with languages where integer overflow is a concern! 🚀

